<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-eTidl_FqdKO8QsF-xor9EA" name="predictability,_QcEyILQqEd6HgZ8EwRW1Og" guid="-eTidl_FqdKO8QsF-xor9EA" changeDate="2010-01-13T07:55:42.859-0800" version="7.5.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Overview&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The primary purpose of estimation is to establish a credible plan for successfully completing a project. Teams strive&#xD;
    to accurately estimate the cost and schedule for delivering a solution that provides value to their stakeholders.&#xD;
    However, estimating a project and producing a plan for its completion does not guarantee success. Unexpected variance&#xD;
    or &lt;em>unpredictability&lt;/em> has the potential to invalidate even the best plans. Successful teams are good at&#xD;
    estimating cost, schedule and the potential for uncertainty. They are also good at dealing with variance. They&#xD;
    acknowledge that uncertainty exists, and they know that to achieve predictability, they must understand and reduce&#xD;
    variance.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For innovative projects with a great deal of uncertainty, precise estimates up front are not demanded because that&#xD;
    would preclude innovation. Instead, the team should focus on reducing uncertainty (which will improve estimates) in the&#xD;
    first half of the project to the extent possible.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Predictability status requires knowing several things:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Are we good at estimating?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Do we have predictable processes?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Are we reducing uncertainty by addressing the unknowns in the project?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Does our team have sufficient skills to successfully complete the project?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Predictability metrics&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Core and Supplementary metrics can help a team determine their predictability status.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Core metrics&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/iteration_velocity_807B594F.html&quot; guid=&quot;_sg-3YOorEdyXraj7Kl_Siw&quot;>Iteration Velocity&lt;/a> measures the pace of the team. It indicates how much work a&#xD;
        team can complete in an iteration by tracking how much work it has successfully delivered in past iterations.&#xD;
        Consistent (predictable) velocity enables the team to better predict how much they can deliver for the remainder of&#xD;
        the project.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Supplementary metrics&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/reduct_risk_est_variance_BB6D6664.html&quot; guid=&quot;_qxjBcOEWEd6AqdnazgLzJg&quot;>Reduction of Risk Estimation Variance&lt;/a> tracks how much estimation variance is&#xD;
        reduced by removing uncertainty in the project. When teams have more confidence in their estimates, their projects&#xD;
        are more predictable.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/planned_vs_actual_effort_DBE6C2F8.html&quot; guid=&quot;_ZkJQQLQyEd6HgZ8EwRW1Og&quot;>Planned Versus Actual Effort&lt;/a> is used to monitor variance in the amount of&#xD;
        actual hours worked compared to the amount planned. This is useful when a more granular level of tracking is&#xD;
        required to monitor predictability. The team can analyze trends at the work item, iteration and release levels to&#xD;
        determine the cause of effort variance and determine what corrective actions to take to improve predictability.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/trend_variance_2C198B83.html&quot; guid=&quot;_kf_ssNYGEd6cgZKT68bL_w&quot;>Trend Variance&lt;/a> tracks cost and schedule variance across the project lifecycle.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Some organizations use metrics such as &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/spi_DA0B6BDE.html&quot; guid=&quot;_cdf3cIpiEd2VgpaHVL4ymQ&quot;>Schedule Performance Index&lt;/a> (SPI) and &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/cpi_1F09D962.html&quot; guid=&quot;_v7dsAIpiEd2VgpaHVL4ymQ&quot;>Cost Performance Index&lt;/a> (CPI) to monitor predictability. However, these metrics&#xD;
        are typically not considered useful in an agile context.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;>Reporting project predictability status in a dashboard&lt;/font>&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The following dashboard example represents one way to calculate and report predictability status. Teams can substitute&#xD;
    metrics that are already used successfully in their organizations for a custom predictability report.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Produce this dashboard by harvesting metrics data and populating a spreadsheet. Generate the dashboard report using&#xD;
    charting capabilities of the spreadsheet tool. Or, the team can use the spreadsheet as a data source and create a&#xD;
    custom report in IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Insight&amp;reg;. Our intent is to provide these types of dashboards over time as out of the&#xD;
    box reports in IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Insight&amp;reg;.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    To assess a project's predictability status with this dashboard, the following inputs are needed (provided by the&#xD;
    predictability core metrics and team-specific variables):&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;table title=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;WIDTH: 894px; HEIGHT: 433px&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; width=&quot;894&quot; border=&quot;1&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td width=&quot;25%&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div class=&quot;style1&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Value&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td width=&quot;75%&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div class=&quot;style1&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Description&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;strong>PREDICTED_VELOCITY&lt;/strong>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Number of points estimated to be delivered in the next iteration. This is typically based on velocity of&#xD;
                the team in the prior completed iteration. This number is adjusted as needed to allow for reduced/&#xD;
                increased staff, or other events expected to impact productivity of the team.&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;strong>ACTUAL_VELOCITY&lt;/strong>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Number of points actually delivered in the last iteration.&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>MINIMUM_VELOCITY_TOLERANCE&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Minimum acceptable variance in velocity (as a percentage) based on the level of uncertainty or expected&#xD;
                    variance for the project. This percentage will be lower for new development projects and projects&#xD;
                    supported by new technologies than for maintenance projects, or projects where the problem area is well&#xD;
                    understood.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Example: If the team's actual velocity is expected to stay within 10% of predicted velocity, set the&#xD;
                    MINIMUM_VELOCITY_TOLERANCE at 90%.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;strong>VELOCITY_VARIANCE&lt;/strong>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Actual variance (as a percentage) between predicted and actual velocity. This represents the&#xD;
                    predictability regarding the capacity of the team. Calculate as follows: ACTUAL_VELOCITY /&#xD;
                    PREDICTED_VELOCITY&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Reporting predictability status&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is difficult to establish red, yellow, and green definitions for a predictability status that would apply in all&#xD;
    project contexts. Different types of projects have different levels of expected variance. Projects that are likely to&#xD;
    have many unknowns that must be addressed throughout the lifecycle can expect to be less predictable than projects with&#xD;
    low risk and familiar technologies. In addition, the industry is still learning about this area as organizations begin&#xD;
    to implement metrics to monitor their projects' predictability. As more data becomes available from project experience&#xD;
    with these metrics, dashboard status definitions will improve incrementally.&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p>The following table shows how the predictability status is calculated for the dashboard.&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;table style=&quot;WIDTH: 944px; HEIGHT: 363px&quot; width=&quot;944&quot; border=&quot;4&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;th scope=&quot;col&quot; width=&quot;99&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Status&lt;/font>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/th>&#xD;
            &lt;th scope=&quot;col&quot; width=&quot;421&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Definition&lt;/font>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/th>&#xD;
            &lt;th scope=&quot;col&quot; width=&quot;269&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Actions to Take&lt;/font>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/th>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ff0000&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>RED&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ffffff&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;br />&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    VELOCITY_VARIANCE &amp;lt; MINIMUM_VELOCITY_TOLERANCE&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    The team delivered fewer points in the last iteration than they predicted, and their velocity variance&#xD;
                    is greater than the tolerance level set for the project, Predictability is at risk.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ffffff&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    The team should spend time in the iteration retrospective meeting to determine what is driving the&#xD;
                    variance in their estimates. Were there special circumstances in the iteration that temporarily&#xD;
                    impacted the team's velocity? Or is the team consistently delivering below their estimates?&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    If the trend is probably not going to improve, or if the impact is too high, the team should&#xD;
                    collaborate with stakeholders to determine whether the release plan should be adjusted in terms of&#xD;
                    scope or schedule.&lt;br />&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#33CC66&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>GREEN&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    VELOCITY_VARIANCE &amp;gt;= MINIMUM_VELOCITY_TOLERANCE&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    The team delivered the predicted number of points or more than the predicted number of points. Or their&#xD;
                    velocity variance is within the tolerance level set for the project.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Good job! The project is becoming predictable. The team is addressing uncertainty throughout the&#xD;
                    lifecycle, has adopted predictable processes, and apparently has the essential set of skills for the&#xD;
                    project.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Do not assume that accurate estimates for a few iterations guarantee predictability, however. Continue&#xD;
                    to monitor velocity variance throughout the lifecycle so that sudden spikes or a trend of increasing&#xD;
                    variance can be identified and analyzed.&lt;br />&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ffff00&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>YELLOW&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    status is red, but we have a plan to address the issue&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Analyze Predictability metrics to determine the causes for the unexpected variance. If variance is high&#xD;
                    enough to affect the schedule or cost, collaborate with stakeholders to determine what actions to take&#xD;
                    and create a plan to address the issues. Follow the plan and monitor progress in each iteration until&#xD;
                    status is green.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Consult the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../publish.bus.practices_for_perf_measurement.base-ibm/customcategories/improve_predictability_C40A0DA6.html&quot; guid=&quot;_3uvHILbFEd6_i8GY7ieNyA&quot;>Predictability Value Traceability Tree&lt;/a> which can help you identify&#xD;
                    strategies and solutions to improve predictability.&lt;br />&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Considerations&#xD;
&lt;/h3>The following factors impact predictability:&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;table title=&quot;&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; width=&quot;85%&quot; border=&quot;1&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;strong>Process&lt;/strong>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Side effects of unpredictable or inefficient processes can impact predictability. When teams do not&#xD;
                    consistently follow best practices appropriate for the project, it is impossible to be forecast&#xD;
                    accurately. When new processes are introduced to a team, estimates should reflect additional time for&#xD;
                    adjustment.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;strong>Estimation&lt;/strong>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Poor estimation skills result in a project that is unpredictable. The following recommendations can&#xD;
                    help improve the accuracy of team estimates:&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;ul>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Do not estimate work in chunks that are too large. The larger the task, the more room for error&#xD;
                        there is in estimation. Break large tasks down into a number of smaller work items.&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Do not estimate too far out into the future. Provide just-in-time detailed estimates during&#xD;
                        iteration planning for all work items planned for that iteration.&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Do not provide estimates for work that will be performed by another team member. However, team&#xD;
                        members should collaborate to validate individual estimates as needed.&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        When it is too difficult to provide an estimate for a particular work item, the team must take&#xD;
                        action to resolve any open issues. Address uncertainty throughout the lifecycle rather than waiting&#xD;
                        until the end to deal with outstanding issues.&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        When requirements are not detailed enough, estimates are likely to be off-target. Perform&#xD;
                        sufficient analysis and receive clarification as needed before producing detailed estimates for&#xD;
                        iteration planning.&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                &lt;/ul>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;strong>Uncertainty&lt;/strong>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Reducing uncertainty is essential for project predictability. Uncertainty affects the ability of the&#xD;
                    team to have high confidence in their estimates and it can cause serious disruption to the productivity&#xD;
                    of the team. These factors are among those that contribute to uncertainty:&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;ul>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        New or changing technologies&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Outsourced resources with unknown processes and skills&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Requirements changes&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Architecture surprises&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                &lt;/ul>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;strong>Team Skills&lt;/strong>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    If no one on the team has certain skills that you need predictability is at risk. Estimates provided by&#xD;
                    team members who do not have required knowledge of the technology or a particular area of the system&#xD;
                    are not reliable. Redistribute tasks to match the appropriate skills with work items for maximum&#xD;
                    accuracy in estimation and efficiency in completing the work. Get mentors and training as needed when a&#xD;
                    lack of specific skills jeopardizes the predictability of the project.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Pitfalls and countermeasures for predictability metrics&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Predictability is only an indicator of project success, it does not guarantee the health of your project. The team&#xD;
    might be very good at estimating, but stakeholders may not be happy with the cost or the schedule that the team&#xD;
    predicts.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is important to analyze the suggested countermeasures for each core predictability metric to confirm that they are&#xD;
    encouraging the appropriate behavior. The team might appear to be very accurate with their estimates, but they might be&#xD;
    sacrificing quality by reducing the time spent testing to ensure that theydeliver within their estimates. Monitor&#xD;
    customer satisfaction to confirm that stakeholders are comfortable with any scope removed to make up for project&#xD;
    underestimation.&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
